@Node Readme
In this doc I refer to the text file as 'picture' or 'pic' or 'image'.  The
program  is  named  "Sigmaker" because it originally was meant for creating
.signature-files.

This program _should_ work on all Amigas (at least after some fiddling with
boot  settings), and multitask happily.  Press left-Amiga-A to swap between
WB/SigMaker.   SigMaker was compiled under Amos Pro, so it is slightly more
intuition-friendly  than the "older" Amos programs.  No need to kill screen
blankers, unless your blanktime is less than 6 seconds :-)

NTSC users note:  Switch your Amy to PAL.
@Endnode

##SigMaker   needs   the   Req.library   in
##libs:-directory  in  order  to  run.   LDos  made it possible to easily use
##req.library requester, so of course I used it - the standard Amos requester
##works,  but  is awful to use.  Every time SigMaker uses the requester, Amos
##will  switch back to WorkBench screen.  If you use ReqChange, then SigMaker
##will  of  course  use  the  ReqTools-requester.   If  you  don't  have  the
##appropriate libraries in Libs:, SigMaker will, sooner or later, crash.  You
##are warned during setup if the Req.Library is not found.


@node Description

                   The nightmare of your fellow netters.


                                 SigMaker


                 In .netland no-one can hear you scream...


I  got tired of making those awful ascii pics with a text editor, character
by  character...   The bitmap-to-ascii-converters I have seen have done the
trick  by printing a line of text, moving the "cursor" down a pixel or two,
and then printing again...  Nice, but (as far as I know) only works on Amy.
What  I  was looking for was a kind of painting program, but with which you
could paint with characters.  I found no such program (except AnsiPaint and
Ansi  Editor,  and they were not exactly what I was looking for), so I made
this  program.   It probably has some bugs, and it is not very "intuitive",
but it works.
@Endnode

@node Installation
                               Installation:

Copy  SigMaker, SigMakerBanks.Abk and SigMaker.guide to some directory, and
assign  "SigMaker:"  to that directory.  The program DOES NOT WORK....  (!)
...unless  this  document file is found during setup!  I know you hate this
feature,  and  so  do  I,  but  I know guys who distribute programs without
document  files  and  _I_hate_it_.   Soo...   deleting this doc file is not
wise.     The    program    checks    that    there   is   a   file   named
"SigMaker:SigMaker.guide"  and that it is of the right size,but not what it
contains  or  anything  like  that.   You  can  move  this  doc to "Docs:",
"Documents:" or whatever you call your doc directory, as long as there is a
assign  to this dir.  But remember not to modify this file in any way.  The
only  way  to  pack this file and still have SigMaker running is to pack it
with  the  XFH/XPK  system  or  similar so that SigMaker thinks it's in the
right place and of the right size.

SigMaker  uses  the  "s:"-directory  to store its config file.  There's one
included in this archivem, with the MagicWB's color settings.

The amos.library file must be copied to "libs:".
@endnode

@node Parameters

	Cli usage:    SigMaker [wWidth hHeight]
	Example:      SigMaker w320 h256

The  minimum  accepted  line  width is 80, the biggest is 255.  The minimum
accepted  height is 50, the biggest is limited by the amount of free memory
you have.

Example:   "SigMaker  h60  w25"  reserves  memory  for 60 lines that are 80
characters  wide (25 is too small a number) (Note:  If someone knows how to
read  tooltypes  from  Amos,  tell me).  If there are no arguments given or
they  is  too small/big, SigMaker will use the default values of height:700
and  width:80.   Only  the  argument containing the wrong value is replaced
with  default  value,  so "w30 h51" becomes "w80 h51", not "w80 h700".  The
program  just  allocates  mem  for  this  exact  amount of lines and cannot
allocate more if needed.  The same applies to the width - you cannot change
the  line width while running SigMaker without erasing the current pic, the
spare  screen  and the undo bank.  Ugly, but not Sierra-ugly.  You can work
your   way   around   this  by  saving  the  picture  before  changing  the
height/width, and then loading the pic back to SigMaker.

Check out this note about @{" Memory usage " Link Memorynote}
@endnode

