@Node Startup
@TOC Instructions
When  you run SigMaker, you will be presented a simple requester.  You must
press  either  left  or  right mouse button to answer these questions.  The
first one is about whether you want an interlaced screen (50 lines tall) or
a  non-interlaced  screen  (25 lines tall).  Then you are asked whether you
want to run SigMaker in "Mono" or "Color" mode.  Mono is _much_ faster, but
you can only paint with foreground color (FG) 1 and background color (BG) 2
(SigMaker  has  8  colors  to choose from).  Plus, the "Colorize" and "Pick
Color"-options  are  only available in color mode.  WARNING!  If you change
colourmode  while  editing a picture, the colors WILL get screwed up if you
change  from  color  to  mono  mode  (as  the color definitions will all be
replaced  with  settings BG0/FG1).  Changing from mono to color does not do
any harm, except slowing things down.
@Endnode

@Node Screens
@TOC Instructions
                 The display is divided in three sections:

The  largest and uppermost is the Edit screen.  This is where you paint the
picture.

The green stripe below the edit screen is the status screen. It displays
the following info:

Current  coordinates, current pic size, comment, options that are currently
ON and current primary/secondary characters.
The option characters:	B	Brush in memory
						Z	Colorize mode on
						C	Continuous draw on
						T	Brush transparencyon
						R	Replace mode on

The  lowest part is used by some functions, and contains a nice logo, so it
is of great importance really...  (sigh).
@Endnode

@Node Picsize
@TOC Instructions
You can edit 80*700 characters pics as default with this version.  To use a
different # of lines or different line width, start SigMaker from Shell and
give it some arguments.  See @{" CLI parameters " Link Parameters}.

The  width/height  can  also  be  changed  any  time  by selecting the "Pic
Size"-menu  item from the "Project"-menu.  You are presented a requester in
which  you  must  type the new width and height values.  The minimum values
accepted  are width:80 and height:25/50, depending on whether you are using
an   interlaced   edit  screen.   The  Maximum  values  are  width:255  and
height:Whatever  you  wish.  After the right values have been typed in, you
will  be  asked  if  you  are really, really sure.  Select yes and the pic,
spare screen and the undo bank are all cleared.

@{" A word about mem usage / colors " Link MemoryNote}
@Endnode

@node Drawing
@TOC Instructions
The  current  coordinates are in the status screen's left side.  The number
after  'L:'-characters right after the coordinates represents the number of
the last line in current drawing.

You  have  the  basic free draw, line, box, ellipse (this works for circles
too  :-)  and  fill  commands,  and  you can load/save pics as normal ascii
files.   When  in  color  mode,  the  fill  command  will  stop  filling to
characters  that  differ  from  the ones in the area to be painted, OR have
different  color.  So you can create pics that consist of nothing more than
different BG colored spaces, and still use the Fill command.

The  program  is in "free draw" mode most of the time.  In this mode, press
any  normal  character  key  to  change  the character you paint with.  The
selected  char is visible in the right side of status screen.  Combinations
with  shift/alt work.  With every drawing function, some rules apply:  left
mouse  button  paints  the  object  with  the primary character.  Right one
paints with the secondary character, and ESC, when pressed before the mouse
keys, aborts the function (abort does not work in free draw mode, though).

Use mouse to draw.  The left button paints with the selected character, and
the right one "erases", that is, paints with the secondary paint character,
which  is  space  (ascii  32)  as default.  To make the paint character the
secondary  character,  press  F5.  To reset the secondary character back to
space,   1st   press   space   and   then   F5.    You  can  also  use  the
"Char->Sec.Char"-menu  instead  of  pressing  F5.   To  reset the secondary
character to space, press F4 or use the menu.

The  secondary character is also important for another reason:  If SigMaker
is  in  "Replace"-mode  (indicated by a letter "R" on the right side of the
status  screen),  you  can  only  paint  on characters that are the same as
secondary  character!!!   So,  for  example pasting a brush when in replace
mode may seem not to do anything.  Experiment with the "Replace"-mode ON to
see  what  I mean.  Replace mode affects every drawing function there is in
SigMaker,  and that's why ChillButter(tm) (more about this later) turns the
Replace  mode  off  before converting a pic.  As the secondary character is
ascii 32 (space) as default, by turning the replace mode on you can draw on
top  of existing pic without erasing any part of it (except the spaces) - a
bit  like in Dpaint's Stencil-mode.  Note!!!  "Replace" does not care about
color settings.  If your secondary character is space, then you can draw on
ALL spaces in the picture, no matter what BG color they have.

When  you  select a draw-function, the status screen will present some info
about  how  to  use  that drawing function.  The program will return to the
normal    drawing    mode    after    you   have   finished   drawing   the
ellipse/line/whatever.   So,  to  draw  multiple  lines,  you must press F6
multiple  times,  and  so  on.   A  bit odd behaviour from the program, but
you'll get used to it.

Esc    aborts    the    line/box/ellipse/fill   options.    Selecting   the
areas/characters  with  RIGHT  mouse  button  will  paint  the  object with
secondary  character.   Using  left  mouse  button means that primary paint
character is used.
@Endnode

@Node Menus
@TOC Instructions
The  menus  are  activated  in an almost-standard way:  by moving the mouse
pointer to the top line of the edit screen and holding down the right mouse
button,  in  a  similar  fashion  to  Dpaint.   Press  DEL to erase current
drawing.   F6-F10 can be used draw lines ellipses, boxes, texts and to fill
areas  instead of selecting these functions from the 'draw'-menu.  Pressing
right Amiga key at the same time with some of these will alter the effect -
this  is  indicated  in the menus by a letter "A" ahead of the function key
abbreviation.  "A-F8" means "Right Amiga-F8".
@Endnode

@Node Scrolling
@TOC Instructions
To  scroll  the  visible  area  up/down,  use cursor up/down-keys.  If your
picture  has,  say, 72 lines, and you scroll the screen downwards to reveal
line  73,  the  height  of your picture (the # of lines) will grow.  If you
scroll  the  screen back up and the last line in your picture is blank, the
number of lines will decrease by one (This is why scrolling up sometimes is
slower  than  scrolling  down  when editing pics with wide lines:  SigMaker
checks long lines slower than short lines).

To scroll sideways, use the cursor left/right keys.

Another  way  to scroll while in free draw mode is to hold down the Control
key  while moving the mouse.  Both horizontal and vertical positions of the
flashing  cursor  affect  the  visible  area's  position  in picture in the
following  way:   the  farther  away from the center of the edit screen the
pointer  is,  the  more the screen will scroll to that direction.  The same
with  other  words:   When you hit ctrl, the screen will be centered around
the character the pointer was on.  Holding down ctrl will center the screen
again and again until you've reached the border of the picture.

Your  current  vertical position is indicated by the "slider bar" in either
left or right side of the screen.  The slider bar CAN NOT be used to scroll
up/down,  as  it  is  nothing  more  than an indicator built up of hardware
sprites.   The  indicator will jump back and forth all the time as you move
the  mouse  - the indicator always is positioned so that it isn't overlayed
on  the  part of the screen you are editing.  I made the indicator this way
because  there was no space left anywhere on the screen :-) and overscanned
screen somehow didn't work.  :-O

The  horizontal  position  is  only shown if the line width is more than 80
characters.   If  the line width is more than 80 chars, two markers will be
in  either  top  or bottom part of the edit screen.  These work in the same
manner as the vertical indicator.
@Endnode

@Node Autoshade
@TOC Instructions
You   can   set   the   "shade"-characters   (more   about   these  in  the
"ChillButter(tm)"-section)  by  selecting  the  "AutoShade"-menu item - you
cannot  change  the characters once you are in ChillButter(tm), so remember
to  set  them  now.   As AutoShade helps the user, I'm not gonna write much
about it, except:  (R)everse reverses the strings characters - handy if you
are  going to print the converted picture (paper usually is white, so space
is the brightest character on paper), or if your text's background color is
white.   The  (M)anual  selection  shows  2  areas  filled  with  different
characters.   You  just  have to select the one you think is darker.  After
some  64+63+62+...+1  questions the characters are in order, if you haven't
made  any  mistakes  :-).   The  (A)utoshade-option arranges the characters
automatically  so that the ones with least pixels are on the left, the ones
with  most  pixels  on  the  right.   Please note:  AutoShade only uses the
characters  that  are  in  the shade-string already.  So select the desired
characters into string BEFORE arranging them.  I have noticed that round or
otherwise  symmetrical  characters look better in converted pics than, say,
slash-characters  ("/"'s).   Also note that character with more pixels than
another  does  not automatically mean it looks darker or lighter (depending
on  palette, but in these docs I assume the background color is black) than
the  other  -  it  also  depends  on  how  the pixels are positioned in the
character.   SigMaker  will save the string upon exit, and load it when you
run  SigMaker  the  next  time.  The file name of SigMaker's config file is
"s:SigMaker.config".   Make sure your boot disk/partition is write enabled.
Cursor left/right and right mouse button also have functions, test them.

Note:   when  you exit the AutoShade, you will be asked whether you want to
replace  all  the old shade-characters with the corresponding new ones.  So
if  the  old  2nd  darkest  char  was  'Ł'  and  the  new  one  is '-', ALL
'Ł'-characters  in  the  pic  will be replaced with '-'.  And this is where
everything  often  goes  wrong.  Imagine your old 7th darkest character was
'-'.  SigMaker now replaces all '-' characters in your pic with the new 7th
darkest character - but just a moment ago SigMaker replaced some characters
with  this  very  same '-'!!!  So...  now both 2nd and 7th darkest areas in
your  pic  are  painted with the new 3rd darkest character!!!  These errors
just  accumulate,  and  in the worst cases, after SigMaker has done all the
replacing,  half  of  your  pic  is painted all wrong.  So:  ALWAYS SET THE
SHADES  FIRST,  AND  ONLY  THEN USE ChillButter(tm)!!!!  This way you don't
have to play with the AutoShade's replace-function.
@Endnode

@Node Brushes
@TOC Instructions
The  "Transparency" setting in Brush-menu means whether the Space character
in  brushes substitutes any existing characters in picture when you "paste"
the  brush.   This  is indicated by "T" on the status screen.  A "B" on the
status  screen  indicates  that  you  have  a  brush in memory, ready to be
pasted.  You can only paste when a brush is created by selecting "cut" from
brush menu.  Maximum size of brush is the size of an interlaced edit screen
-  that  is,  80*50 characters.  As the brush bob (The brush bob is created
when  you  cut  a brush, to speed up the brush displaying) is only drawn on
the  1st  bitplane  to  save  some  chipmem,  it may not be visible on some
colors.  This is unavoidable.

The  "load  brush"  and "save brush"-options differ little from normal load
and  save-options.   A  fileselector  opens, asking you to select the brush
file.   "Clear  Brush" erases the brush in memory and frees the chip memory
used for the brush bob.
@Endnode

@Node Misc2
@TOC Instructions
You  can  insert lines to the pic, if the current length of the pic is less
than  the  given  maximum # lines (defined by giving the "hHeight" argument
when  running  the program, remember?).  Move mouse pointer to the line you
want  to  move  downwards, and press Return (the one above right shift, not
the  numpad  one).   The  line, and everything after it, will move one line
down,  an  empty line will appear and the length of the pic is increased by
one line.

To  remove  lines,  move  the  cursor  to  appropriate line and press right
shift+backspace.   The  line will disappear, and everything after that line
will  move  upwards.   The  length of the pic will decrease by one.  If you
want  just  to erase text from a line and not completely remove it from the
list, use some drawing mode (line, free draw).
@Endnode

@Node Textmode
@TOC Instructions
When  in  text  mode,  the  program is in overwrite mode all the time - you
cannot change to insert mode.

Backspace  erases  text  from the left without moving the rest of the line.
"Del" key does not work.

You  can  scroll  screen while in text mode.  Just hold down left shift and
use the cursor keys.

Althought  the  menus  are not available while in text mode, you can change
the colors at any time by pressing TAB.
@Endnode

@Node Characters
@TOC Instructions
As  I said before, the program is made with Amos basic.  So it does not use
the normal system keymaps, but instead the Amos' own, "Swedish" keymap.

To  make  the  more  unusual  characters easily available, I added an Ascii
character  list  a  la Atari ST's FirstWord(+).  Press 'HELP' or select the
"character  list" menu item from "Other"-menu to display this screen.  Then
just  click  on  the  desired  character.  If you select the character with
right  mouse  button, it will be selected as the secondary paint character.
Characters 32-255 are visible, as characters 0-31 have a special use.

Using   rarely   seen  characters  is  a  bit  risky,  as  not  nearly  all
systems/fonts have 'em all.  The Amos' font has many characters I have seen
nowhere  else.   These  are used for window borders etc.  It is not wise to
use them in your pics.

You  can  also "pick" the character under cursor as primary paint character
by  pressing  F2.   Pressing  "Right  Amiga-F2"  picks  the  COLORS  of the
character  under  the  cursor,  not  the  character.  You can only pick the
PRIMARY  char  this way - but if you select the "Pick Character" menu item,
left button will pick the char as primary and right button as the secondary
paint  character.   Esc  will  abort  the  pick  procedure and keep the old
colors/characters.
@Endnode

@Node Spare
@TOC Instructions
SigMaker  holds  two  screens  simultaneously.   "Clear",  "load",  "save",
"replace"  etc.  only affect the visible one.  To swap between the screens,
press  F1  or select "Swap <> Spare" menu item.  The second screen is ideal
for  creating  brushes  or  experimenting  with various functions.  The two
screens work identically, so I decided not to indicate in any way which one
of the two is visible.
@EndNode

@Node Undo
@TOC Instructions
If  you  screw something up, you can use the Undo-function.  Just press ESC
once,  and the screens returns to what it was like before you did the dirty
deed.   Press  it  twice,  and  the  screen resets back to what it was like
before the first Esc-press.

Every  time  you  start  drawing  in freehand mode, use the menu or use any
function that affects the picture, the picture bank is copied into the undo
bank.   When  you  press  esc, the two banks are swapped and the picture is
redrawn.   Not  only  the  visible area, but the whole picture is stored in
undo bank.  NOTE!!!  The spare screen and the current screen share the undo
bank  -  so  if  you swap to spare screen and press ESC (undo), the picture
stored  from  the  other screen is drawn on spare screen!!  If you do this,
press  Esc again to save the spare screen's contents.  DO NOT DRAW ANYTHING
ON  THE  SCREEN  OR  USE THE MENU OR THE IMAGE WILL BE LOST!  You have been
warned.

After using ChillButter(tm), the undo bank holds the old picture in it, but
only  if  you  haven't used the (N)ew or (A)gain-options.  If you have, the
Undo  bank  holds  the previous converted picture.

If,  when  exiting  Autoshade, you replace the old shade chars with the new
ones,  undo  bank will hold the original picture in unchanged form.  If the
replace goes badly, press Esc.

As  I  stated  above, using the menus copies current pic to the undo bank -
even  if  you  select  function  that  doesn't  affect  the  picture,  like
"About"-screen!   I did it this way because otherwise I would've had to add
calls  to  the  undo-procedure  almost  everywhere  in  the  code.   Sorry.
@Endnode

@node ChillButter

----------------------------- ChillButter(tm) -----------------------------

You  may  have  noticed  the menu item "ChillButter(tm)" in the Other-menu.
This  is  the  name  I  gave  to  SigMaker's  internal iff-to-ascii picture
converter.

This program outputs 64 different characters.  It uses characters stored in
a  special "Shade"-string. See @{"AutoShade" Link Autoshade}.
The  characters  represent  the average brightness of colours in X*Y pixels
sections  of  the  original  iff  picture  -  the first character being the
darkest  and  the  last  being the brightest.  ChillButter(tm) outputs only
"mono"  images.   If  SigMaker  is  in Color mode, ChillButter will use the
current  FG/BG  colors  in  it's converted pics.  After converting, use the
"Colorize"-function   to   add  color.   Replace  mode  has  no  effect  on
ChillButter.   The  old  image  is  stored in Undo bank when ChillButter is
summoned.

After the picture is converted to blocks, you can output the X*Y characters
matrix  to  either  screen  (You can only preview it on screen in interlace
mode  (??)), printer (PRT:) or disk file.  A file requester opens, and asks
for  the file name.  You can also select "Again" to try converting the same
picture  again  with different settings.  The "Preview"-functions shows you
64  lines  of  the  converted  pic  on an interlaced hires screen.  You can
scroll this screen by using cursor up/cursor down keys.  The screen scrolls
10  lines  up/down,  unless  there  are  not  that  many  lines left in the
beginning/end.   If  this  is  the  case, the screen only scrolls one line.
Selecting  "Edit" returns you to SigMaker's editor, the newly-converted pic
ready  to  be  edited.   You  may  need  to change screenmode and/or adjust
palette to make something out of the ascii pic...  :-)

Pictures  with any detail in them are not converted well, but pictures that
have  large  areas  of  same colour in them and big differences in contrast
usually  convert  well.  Pictures with less pixels horizontally than is the
line  width in characters convert almost perfectly, as no pixel information
is lost.  Try using HamLab, AdPro or something similar to first convert the
original image to a 32-color, X pixels wide iff picture, and only then load
it  in  ChillButter(tm).  Do not use dithering.  Set the line width to be a
multiple   of   the  picture's  width.   ChillButter(tm)  _should_  convert
halfbright pics ok, but it does not.  Dunno why.

BTW, ChillButter(tm) is orcish for "Clerics are Stupid".  Or maybe not.
@endnode

