##Ansi Editor (for creating Ansi anims... simple but works) !ADD THIS!

@node Misc

                                   Notes


I  have  no idea about how much memory this program needs (I've had no time
to  check  it out).  The first time you run SigMaker, it will select random
screen  colors.   Modify  the  palette  (and the Shade string) and when you
select "Quit", the colors will be saved to "s:SigMaker.config".

If  the  pics  are  meant  for  doc  files  etc, use only colors 0-3.  Most
A500-guys  I know (including me) run WB in 4-color mode for some odd reason
:-) Remember also that the color values are not saved in the ascii pics, so
with  99% probability the picture's colors will be wrong when it is viewed.
It  is  safest  to  use  the standard 2.0 grayshades+blue as the first four
colors  in  SigMaker.   You  can  create  nice middleshades by printing for
example "#"-characters on different colored background.

The  color  functions  are  NOT optimized.  I wrote the program in a highly
modular  way.   The  result:   hundreds and hundreds of calls to procedures
that  could be substituted with just a couple of pokes/peeks.  Maybe I will
one  day,  when  I  am  100% sure that these procedures will not change any
more,  optimize  the  code  a bit.  I experimented with various methods and
noticed that screen redraw was more that twice as fast as it is now when no
procedure  calls  were  used.  But as this program is not nearly "complete"
yet, I thought that a nice-looking code weights more than faster operation.

The  "Save  Ansi"-option  will  reset  the  color settings back to defaults
(BG0/FG1)  at  the  end  of the ansi file, so displaying them in shell them
does not screw up your shell window's colors.

The ellipse and fill functions only affect the visible area of the picture.
To  paint  areas  larger  than  screen,  you must paint once, scroll, paint
again, and so on.

This  is  because  the line/box/ellipse commands work in the following way:
they use the normal Amos graphics functions in the little 80*50 pix area on
the  lowest screen, and then transfer the results to the ascii pic.  I made
the  program this way because it was fast'n'EASY (I can imagine how slow an
ellipse-function  written  from scratch, in basic, by me, would be :-) (Hey
this rhymes!  I'm a poet after all)) , but this method has its flaws.  Hmm.
My sentence structures are starting to get interesting.

Every  time  some  procedure  clears  an area, adds lines, clears the whole
drawing or something similar, the new area/lines will use the current FG/BG
colors.  So, if you for example add a line in the middle of an picture with
black BG color and your current BG color is pink, a pink line will appear.

(In the next paragraph "X" means the line width).

The  programs  handles  the  horizontal  lines of the asciipic as (surprise
surprise) strings, stored in an Amos memory bank.  Everything is loaded one
line at a time, and then converted to X chars long strings.  If you load an
ascii  file  that  consists  of  long  lines,  the  lines  with more than X
characters in them will be truncated.  To avoid this, load the file to some
editor  and  save  it  back.  Most editors save the file as separate lines,
while some (TransWrite Jr2, for example) saves the paragraph as long lines.
When you save a pic, all spaces that are in the right-side end of the lines
will  be  removed.   All  blank  lines  in  the beginning or the end of the
picture  will  be  removed  as  well.   Empty pics are not saved.  All this
applies  to  the  printing too.  If you want the pic to have blank lines in
the  end,  add  them with some editor, or add them via shell by redirecting
'echo " "'s output, or something like that.

The  colors  are  converted  to  have  values  0-255  (8  bits)  during the
iff->ascii  conversion  to  eliminate  the rounding errors in calculations.
Block  sizes  are  always  rounded  to integers to make the process faster.
Imagine you have 4*8 pixels area of brightness 7, and after it a 4*8 pixels
area  of  brightness  8,  and  a  block  size of 8*8.  Normally the average
brightness  would  be  7 ((7+8)/2) when converted to integer.  In SigMaker,
the average brightness is int((16*7+16*8)/2.0/4+.5)=30 , meaning that shade
character 30 (31st character in the shade string) is used.

The  handling of memory banks was made faster by the use of @{" LDos " Link
LDos}.
Replacing   characters,   for   example,   was  reduced  from  hundreds  of
Mid$()-functions  to one LReplace-command.  *KABOOM* I llllike it!  And, it
seems that the LDos' Lbstr/Lstr commands are about 1.6 times as fast as the
Amos Pro's Peek$/Poke$-commands.
@Endnode

@Node Memorynote
Note:   if  you  give,  say,  "h1000" and "w100" as parameters, the program
needs  6*(100*1000)  bytes  of memory - as it allocates one memory bank for
the  picture,  one  for  spare screen and one for the "undo"-option to play
with,  and  each  bank  takes  width*height bytes of memory.  Each of these
three  banks  is  associated with another bank of the same size, containing
the  color settings.  Even when in "mono" mode, the program does create the
color  banks (Each byte in this bank contains the fore/background colors of
the  "same"  byte  in  the character bank - 4 first bits for the foreground
color  and  4  last  bits  for  the  background color.  So, in theory, this
program  can  work  in  16-color  mode.   But  as far as I know, Ansi color
sequences  support  only  9 (?) colors, and this is why SigMaker can create
max.   8  color pics - handling 3 bits instead of 4 is faster, and 9 colors
would require a 16-color screen).
@Endnode

@Node LDos
                     ----==== COMMERCIAL TIME ====----

                Ldos (c) Niklas Sjöberg 2:203/415.3@Fidonet

    From LDos' documentation (empty lines deleted from here and there):

--------------------------------------------------------------------->8---
       What you just have received  is  a  new  fast,  and  efficient
    extension  for  AMOS  V1.3  and higher. It is supposed to correct
    some misfeatures of AMOS and add some functions not available  in
    AMOS.  The  official  name  is 'Ldos' which seemed logical when I
    started out, but since that a lot other functions have been added
    which are far from DOS-functions. I got the idea about Ldos after
    waiting over fifteen (15!) minutes for Line Input to read  a  300
    Kb  textfile from floppy. After 15 minutes I stopped the program,
    it still wasn't finished :-) Then  I  thought,  "while  I  am  at
    it..", and I came up with some new interesting commands.

       Here is a small featurelist of Ldos :

    o New load and save routines.
    o Support for BOTH load and save in the same file without
      reopening it.
    o Ability to save and load from the middle of the file.
    o Up to three channels open simultaneously.

    o Commands for setting/reading :
    o filenotes
    o protectionbits
    o dates
*-  o Environmentvariables

    o Determine filelength without having to assign a channel to
      the file.

    o Determine if a name belongs to a file or a directory.

    o New, very easy to use, directorycommands. Doesn't use any
      bufferspace as AMOS dir-command. Only one name is read at
      the time, unlike AMOS dir-command, meaning no bufferover-
      flow, never to many files in a dir and 0 waittime before
      names can be displayed on screen.
*-    Commands for handling recursive reading and/or popping out
*-    of directory-reading and being w able to return to the exact
*-    position later and continue reading. The number of different
*-    active "popped" directories are only limited by your memory.

*-  o Commands to list all system- assignments, disks, volumes and
*-    other devices and obtaining further information about disks.

    o Fast stringhandling to and from banks. Forget Peek and Poke.

    o Fast replace, and filter-out-function.

    o "Line Input"-commands from buffer. This routine manages to
      "Line Input" >40 Kb/sec on my machine (with an AdSpeed)
      and that includes loadingtime from HD in 1Kb-blocks!

    o Fast time and date-routines. Command for getting the current
      time and date, returned in strings, easy to process. Highly
      optimized.

    o Convert to and from datestamps, does not use slow library-
      functions. Highly optimized.

    o Support for the filerequester in req.library. Totally
      configurable with optional cache (no need to re-read
      the dir) for floppy-users. Pops up on the Workbench.
*-    Also support for font-mode which lets the user pick a
*-    font in a really neat way.
*-    Set a current dir for the requester which doesn't affect
*-    your programs current directory.

    o Commands for decrunching PowerPacker datafiles, all
      compression modes and known versions, without passwordlock.

*-  o Cryptation, DeCryptation with password using a pretty 'hard-
*-    to-crack'-algoritm. (see hints for more info)

    o Commands to handle any device using an IOSTD-stucture,
      specially written with trackdisk.device in mind.

    o Run executable  programs and scripts. Support for I/O in a
      DOS-console window.

    o Load fonts from disk, making them available to Get Rom Fonts
      without needing to scan the whole fonts-directory (sigh!)

    o A complete set of ARexxsupport commands. Create your host,
      start scripts with any name located anywhere on the disk.
      You may also address and send commands to other hosts directly,
      without starting any scripts. All functions are completely
      bullet-proof (on system-level), meaning no software failures.

*-  o Conversion-routine from ANSI/VT100-sequences to AMOS control-codes.
*-    Supports the most frequently used sequences and is much faster
*-    than the console.device's own routines. Highly optimized.

*-  o Word- extraction/count which works similar to the ARexxcommands
*-    Word and Words.Greatly enhances the possibilities for the prog-
*-    rammer to parse configurationsfiles and commandlines.
---------------------------------------------------------------->8--------

Dload  the  evaluation  version  archive  from somewhere, if you're an AMOS
user.  Registration fee is quite small, and includes "LSerial", a nice Amos
Serial extension, also (c) Niklas Sjöberg.
@EndNode

@Node News
v1.33b:
Oooops....   When  something can go wrong, it probably will.  SigMaker1.32b
had  a "little" bug in saving.  Most pics were saved OK, but those that had
different  colored "space"-characters on top/bottom of the image were saved
only  partially.   This  is now fixed.  Furthermore, if your pic had one 80
chars  long  line,  all the lines were saved as 80 chars long.  This is now
fixed  as  well,  the  resulting  ansi  files  should be quite compact now.
Screen display was redrawn after "print"-function for no reason whatsoever,
resulting  in  a couple of sec's delay, and lotsa little misbehaviours here
and there were fixed.

BUT:   I  noticed  a mighty strange thing - "Ansi Load", for example, works
fine  when  the program is not compiled, but sometimes produced odd results
when  the  program IS compiled...  wrong colors in wrong places, and things
like  that  (once  a crash, even!!).  This vastly reduces the usefulness of
this  version :-( and I have no idea how to fix it.  Maybe when the updated
version  of  AmosPro  compiler  comes out...  Most of the time this program
works  on  my  3Mb  A500  flawlessly,  but on my brother's A500 these ghost
"bugs" appear more often.

           THESE OPTIONS ARE NOT DESCRIBED ELSEWHERE IN THE DOCS
                           (at least I think so)
 This part was added because I lack the motivation to update this docfile.


Color mode   (sloooow screen update... uses 8 colors.)
Ansi Load    (Loads an ascii file containing Ansi escape sequences.
              everything but color settings (and characters :-)
              is discarded. Slow.
Ansi Save    (Saves a file containing ansi color settings... Yeah,
              you guessed it - it's s-l-o-w...)
Colorize   Z (for changing the foreground/background colors
              with LMB/RMB. Works in conjuction with Replace, if you
              want it to, and affects ALL draw functions, just like
              Replace mode.)
Continuous C (for toggling continuous line in free draw mode on/off).
Palette      (Use menu or press TAB to toggle it on/off)
Color Box    (visible in color mode only. Shows current FG/BG colors)
Stencil    S (Only certain BG colors can be overwritten. Handy in
              conjuction with brush pasting when transparency-setting
              is off, as only "blank" areas of pic can be replaced with
              the brush image).
^          ^   ^
|          |   Description
|          |
|          Letter on right side of status screen than is displayed if
|          the mode/option/function/whatever is ON.
Function
